{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/707"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.79,0.01,0.04,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40362"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/707"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25174"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40362"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents with a two day history of sudden loss of vision in his right eye. He has no pain but his symptoms are persistent. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and is currently on atorvastatin, ramipril and gliclazide for his hypertension and type 2 diabetes. The right pupil reflex to light was very poor but normal consensual response when light shone in left eye. There was a marked right relative afferent pupillary response. His pupils are dilated with 1% tropicamide and on fundoscopy the fundus of the right eye appears pale compared to the left eye, except for the fovea, which appears red.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Optic neuritis","Central retinal artery occlusion","Endophthalmitis","Acute angle-closure glaucoma","Non-Arteritic Anterior Ischaemic optic neuropathy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESudden onset of painless vision loss along with a pale retina and a \u0027cherry red\u0027 spot at the macula is consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient also has multiple cardiovascular risk factors. The underlying cause can be from the carotid artery, a cardio-embolic source or less commonly secondary to giant cell arteritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOptic neuritis is usually painful and presents with central vision loss. Endophthalmitis, an infection of the tissues and fluids inside the eyeball, is painful and presents with other signs of inflammation including hypopyon, conjunctival injection and periorbital swelling. Acute angle closure glaucoma also presents with pain, halos around light, a fixed dilated pupil, corneal oedema and raised intraocular pressures. Non-arteritis anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy can present with sudden onset of painless vision loss, however the fundus will usually show a swollen optic disc.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A cherry red retinal spot is most consistent with central retinal artery occlusion"],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25174"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevis